HMS Hood was a battle cruiser of the Royal Navy and sunk in the Battle of Denmark Strait on May 24th, 1941. Hood, along with its sister battleship HMS Prince of Wales, were attempting to stop a pair of German ships from breaking out into the North Atlantic to wreck havoc on Allied merchant shipping. Both ships engaged the the German heavy cruiser Prinz Eugen and the legendary battleship Bismark, which resulted severe damage to Prince of Wales and the sinking of Hood, but also contributed to crippling Bismark and forcing it to seek port in occupied France; a move which allowed the Royal Navy to close the noose, ultimately finding and sinking Bismark less than three days later.
